Dental records sent from Germany proved the teeth found in the fire belonged to Mr Ramin.

Germany's Bild said: 'It is the suspicion of the authorities that the hunter carved his victim up, ate parts of the body and burned the remainder along with animals cadavers. He is regarded as a cannibal.'

The island's prosecutor Jose Thorel said a hunt was now underway for 31-year-old Haiti on suspicion he had killed Mr Ramin.

But he insisted reports that Haiti had also eaten his victim were wrong.

Mr Thorel added: 'The theory of cannibalism is in no way a part of our investigation.'

